data = pd.read_csv(filename, names=names)
In [ ]:
data['reason'] = data['reason'].mask(data['reason'] == 0, np.NaN)
data['reason'].dropna(inplace=True)
data['age'] = data['age'].mask(data['age'] < 17, np.NaN)
data['age'].dropna(inplace=True)
data['dist'] = data['dist'].mask(data['dist'] < 1, np.NaN)
data['dist'] = data['dist'].mask(data['dist'] > 500, np.NaN)

data.fillna(data.mean(), inplace=True)
In [ ]:
def plotAttribute(featureName):
    oneSTD = data[featureName].std()
    twoSTD = oneSTD * 2
    threeSTD = oneSTD * 3
    meanValue = data[featureName].mean()
    
    print("Attribue:", featureName.upper())
    print("Summary:")
    instances = data.shape[0]
    outsideTwo = ((data[featureName] < (meanValue - twoSTD)).sum() + (data[featureName] > (meanValue + twoSTD)).sum())
    outsideThree = ((data[featureName] < (meanValue - threeSTD)).sum() + (data[featureName] > (meanValue + threeSTD)).sum())
    
    print("N outside of two STD:\t", outsideTwo, "\t(", round((outsideTwo/instances) *100, 2),"%)")
    print("N outside of three STD:\t", outsideThree, "\t(", round((outsideThree/instances) * 100, 2),"%)")
    

    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue - oneSTD), label='One STD', c="g")
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue + oneSTD), c="g")
    
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue - twoSTD), label='Two STD', c="y")
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue + twoSTD), c="y")
    
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue - threeSTD), label='Three STD', c="r")
    plt.axvline(x=(meanValue + threeSTD), c="r")
    
    data[featureName].hist(figsize=(7,7))
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
 

for attribute in myAtt:
    plotAttribute(attribute)

The correlation between previous and pdays isn't that strong. I believe the reason for this correlation is that for those instances where pdays is -1, previous will always be 0 because if someone has never been contacted before, there's no number of days that have passed since they were contacted.

Binomial Theorem

In [ ]:
# over all confusion matrix
y_predDT  = cross_val_predict(modelDT, X, Y, cv=kfold)
y_predKNN = cross_val_predict(modelKNN, X, Y, cv=kfold)

# Statistics for output 1
meanDT = round(resultsDT.mean()*100.0,2)

# Binomial Theorem
stdDT = math.sqrt((resultsDT.mean()*len(y_predDT))*(1 - resultsDT.mean()))
nDT = len(y_predDT)


# Statistics for output 2
meanKNN = round(resultsKNN.mean()*100.0,2)

# Bionomial Theorem
stdKNN = math.sqrt((resultsKNN.mean()*len(y_predKNN))*(1 - resultsKNN.mean()))
nKNN = len(y_predKNN) 

# T-test must be for indeopendant means (as you are providing two)
result = ttest_ind_from_stats(meanDT, stdDT, nDT, meanKNN, stdKNN, nKNN)


print("\n\nStats Analysis\n---------------------------------------------")
print()
print(result)
print()
print("p-value on its own :", result[1])
print()
if result[1] < 0.05:
    print("Results are statistically significant")
else:
    print("Results are not statistically significant")

array = outData.values
attributes = array[:,0:2]
print(attributes)


print("K-means:\n------------------------------------")
model = KMeans(n_clusters=2)
model.fit(attributes)

# Plotting clusters
cen = model.cluster_centers_
plt.scatter(attributes[ : , 0], attributes[ : , 1], s =50, c='b')
plt.scatter(cen[0][0], cen[0][1], s=200, c='y', marker='s')
plt.scatter(cen[1][0], cen[1][1], s=200, c='r', marker='s')
plt.show()

# cluster labels and saving
print(model.labels_)
attOut = pd.DataFrame(attributes)
classOut = pd.DataFrame(model.labels_)
outData = pd.concat([attOut, classOut], axis=1, sort=False)
outData.to_csv("dataClusters.csv",header=False, index = False)


# elbow method
distance = list()
n_cluster = range(2,30)
for n in n_cluster:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=n)
    model.fit(attributes)
    distance.append(np.average(np.min(cdist(attributes, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)))

plt.plot(n_cluster, distance)
plt.xlabel("Number of clusters")
plt.ylabel("centroid distance")
plt.title('elbow curve')
plt.show()
